# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sip-protocol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging was pioneered in the early Internet era; the IRC protocol was the earliest to achieve wide adoption.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Later in the 1990s, ICQ was among the first closed and commercialized instant messengers, and several rival services appeared afterwards as it became a popular use of the Internet.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Beginning with its first introduction in 2005, BlackBerry Messenger became the first popular example of mobile-based IM, combining features of traditional IM and mobile SMS.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging remains very popular today; IM apps are the most widely used smartphone apps: in 2018 for instance there were 980 million monthly active users of WeChat and 1.3 billion monthly users of WhatsApp, the largest IM network.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging (IM), sometimes also called "messaging" or "texting", consists of computer-based human communication between two users (private messaging) or more (chat room or "group") in real-time, allowing immediate receipt of acknowledgment or reply.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] This is in direct contrast to email, where conversations are not in real-time, and the perceived quasi-synchrony of the communications by the users (although many systems allow users to send offline messages that the other user receives when logging in).
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Earlier IM networks were limited to text-based communication, not dissimilar to mobile text messaging.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] As technology has moved forward, IM has expanded to include voice calling using a microphone, videotelephony using webcams, file transfer, location sharing, image and video transfer, voice notes, and other features.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] IM is conducted over the Internet or other types of networks (see also LAN messenger).
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Depending on the IM protocol, the technical architecture can be peer-to-peer (direct point-to-point transmission) or client–server (when all clients have to first connect to the central server).
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Primary IM services are controlled by their corresponding companies and usually follow the client-server model.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] At one point, the term "Instant Messenger" was a service mark of AOL Time Warner and could not be used in software not affiliated with AOL in the United States.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] For this reason, in April 2007, the instant messaging client formerly named Gaim (or gaim) announced that they would be renamed "Pidgin".
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Modern IM services generally provide their own client, either a separately installed application or a browser-based client.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] They are normally centralised networks run by the servers of the platform's operators, unlike peer-to-peer protocols like XMPP.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] These usually only work within the same IM network, although some allow limited function with other services (see #Interoperability).
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Third-party client software applications exist that will connect with most of the major IM services.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] There is the class of instant messengers that uses the serverless model, which doesn't require servers, and the IM network consists only of clients.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] There are several serverless messengers: RetroShare, Tox, Bitmessage, Ricochet.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Some examples of popular IM services today include Signal, Telegram, WhatsApp Messenger, WeChat, QQ Messenger, Viber, Line, and Snapchat.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The popularity of certain apps greatly differ between different countries.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Certain apps have an emphasis on certain uses - for example, Skype focuses on video calling, Slack focuses on messaging and file sharing for work teams, and Snapchat focuses on image messages.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Some social networking services offer messaging services as a component of their overall platform, such as Facebook's Facebook Messenger, who also own WhatsApp.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Others have a direct IM function as an additional adjunct component of their social networking platforms, like Instagram, Reddit, Tumblr, TikTok, Clubhouse and Twitter; this also includes for example dating websites, such as OkCupid or Plenty of Fish, and online gaming chat platforms.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Private chat allows users to converse privately with another person or a group.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Privacy can also be enhanced in several ways, such as end-to-end encryption by default.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Public and group chat features allow users to communicate with multiple people simultaneously.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Many major IM services and applications offer a call feature for user-to-user voice calls, conference calls, and voice messages.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The call functionality is useful for professionals who utilize the application for work purposes and as a hands-free method.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Videotelephony using a webcam is also possible by some.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Some IM applications include in-app games for entertainment.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Messenger, for example, introduced these where users could play a game and viewed by friends in real-time.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] MSN Messenger featured a number of playable games within the interface.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Facebook's Messenger has had a built-in option to play games with people in a chat, including games like Tetris and Blackjack.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Discord features multiple games built inside the "activities" tab in voice channels.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] A relatively new feature to instant messaging, peer-to-peer payments are available for financial tasks on top of communication.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The lack of a service fee also makes these advantageous to financial applications.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] IM services such as Facebook Messenger and the WeChat 'super-app' for example offer a payment feature.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Though the term dates from the 1990s, instant messaging predates the Internet, first appearing on multi-user operating systems like Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS) and Multiplexed Information and Computing Service (Multics) in the mid-1960s.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Initially, some of these systems were used as notification systems for services like printing, but quickly were used to facilitate communication with other users logged into the same machine.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] CTSS facilitated communication via text message for up to 30 people.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Parallel to instant messaging were early online chat facilities, the earliest of which was Talkomatic (1973) on the PLATO system, which allowed 5 people to chat simultaneously on a 512 x 512 plasma display (5 lines of text + 1 status line per person).
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] During the bulletin board system (BBS) phenomenon that peaked during the 1980s, some systems incorporated chat features which were similar to instant messaging; Freelancin' Roundtable was one prime example.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The first such general-availability commercial online chat service (as opposed to PLATO, which was educational) was the CompuServe CB Simulator in 1980, created by CompuServe executive Alexander "Sandy" Trevor in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] As networks developed, the protocols spread with the networks.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Some of these used a peer-to-peer protocol (e.g. talk, ntalk and ytalk), while others required peers to connect to a server (see talker and IRC).
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The Zephyr Notification Service (still in use at some institutions) was invented at MIT's Project Athena in the 1980s to allow service providers to locate and send messages to users.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Early instant messaging programs were primarily real-time text, where characters appeared as they were typed.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] This includes the Unix "talk" command line program, which was popular in the 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Celerity BBS) also used a similar interface.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Modern implementations of real-time text also exist in instant messengers, such as AOL's Real-Time IM as an optional feature.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] As such, it could be considered a type of graphical user interface (GUI), albeit much more primitive than the later Unix, Windows and Macintosh based GUI IM software.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] OLMs were what Q-Link called "Plus Services" meaning they charged an extra per-minute fee on top of the monthly Q-Link access costs.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Development of the Internet Relay Chat (IRC) protocol began in 1988, and this would become the Internet's first widespread instant messaging standard.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Modern, Internet-wide, GUI-based messaging clients as they are known today, began to take off in the mid-1990s with PowWow, ICQ, and AOL Instant Messenger (AIM).
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Similar functionality was offered by CU-SeeMe in 1992; though primarily an audio/video chat link, users could also send textual messages to each other.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] AOL later acquired Mirabilis, the authors of ICQ; establishing dominance in the instant messaging market.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] A few years later ICQ (then owned by AOL) was awarded two patents for instant messaging by the U.S. patent office.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Meanwhile, other companies developed their own software; (Excite, Microsoft (MSN), Ubique, and Yahoo!), each with its own proprietary protocol and client; users therefore had to run multiple client applications if they wished to use more than one of these networks.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] However, the open protocol IRC continued to be popular by the millennium, and its most popular graphical app was mIRC.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] While instant messaging was mainly in use for consumer recreational purposes, in 1998, IBM launched their Lotus Sametime instant messenger software, the first popular example of enterprise-grade instant messaging.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In 2000, an open-source application and open standards-based protocol called Extensible Messaging and Presence Protocol (XMPP) was launched, initially branded as *Jabber*.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] XMPP servers could act as gateways to other IM protocols, reducing the need to run multiple clients.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Video calling using a webcam also started taking off during this time.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Microsoft's NetMeeting, which was focused on business "web conferencing", was one of the earliest; the company then launched Windows Messenger, coming preloaded on Windows XP, featuring video capabilities.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Messenger added video capabilities in 2001; by 2005, such features were built-in also in AIM, MSN Messenger, and Skype.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] There were a reported 100 million users of instant messaging in 2001.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] As of 2003, AIM was the globally most popular instant messenger with 195 million users and exchanges of 1.6 billion messages daily.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] By 2006, AIM controlled 52 percent of the instant messaging market, but rapidly declined shortly thereafter as the company struggled to compete with other services.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging integrated in other services started picking up pace in the late 2000s.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Myspace, the then-largest social networking service, launched Myspace IM in 2006, shortly after Google's Gtalk, which was integrated into its Gmail webmail interface.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Facebook Chat launched in 2008, providing IM to users of the social network.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] By 2010, traditional instant messaging was in sharp decline in favor of these new messaging features on wider social networks, which at the time were not normally called IM.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] For instance, AIM's userbase had declined by more than half throughout the year 2011.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Standalone instant messenger services were revived, evolving into becoming primarily being used on mobile due to the increasing use of Internet-enabled cell phones and smartphones.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Mobile instant messaging surpassed SMS in global message volume by 2013.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] While SMS relied on traditional paid telephone services, IM apps on mobile were available for free or a minor data charge.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Older IM services were eventually shut, including AIM and Yahoo!
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Messenger, and also Windows Live Messenger, which merged into Skype in 2013.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In 2014, it was reported that instant messaging had more users than social networks.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Concurrently, rising use of instant messaging at workplaces led to the creation of new services (enterprise application integration (EAI)) often integrated with other enterprise applications such as workflow systems, for example in Skype for Business, Slack and Microsoft Teams.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Meanwhile, the launch of Discord in 2015 has marked a notable new example of traditional IM originally designed for desktops.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Most IM protocols are proprietary and are not designed to be interoperable with others, meaning that many IM networks have been incompatible and users have been unable to reach users on other networks.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] As of 2024, fragmentation of IM services means that a typical user is likely to have to use more networks than ever, including the need to download the apps and signing up, to stay in touch with all their contacts.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] However, there had been attempts for solutions.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Multi-protocol clients can use any of the IM protocols by using additional local libraries for each protocol.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Examples of multi-protocol instant messenger software include Pidgin and Trillian, and more recently Beeper.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] These third-party clients have often been unable to keep up due to proprietary protocol restrictions and getting locked out of it.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] For instance, in 2015, WhatsApp started banning users who were using unofficial clients.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Major IM providers usually cite the need for formal agreements, and security concerns as reasons for making changes.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In the early 2000s, when instant messaging was quickly growing, most attempts at producing a unified standard for the-then major IM providers (AOL, Yahoo!, Microsoft) had failed.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] There was a "bitter row" between AOL and its rivals regarding the opening up of their networks.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In 2000, U.S. regulatory Federal Communications Commission (FCC) proposed, and supported by Microsoft chairman Bill Gates, that AOL providing interoperability of its AIM and ICQ instant messengers with Microsoft's MSN Messenger was a condition for the forthcoming AOL-Time Warner merger.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] However, in 2004, Microsoft, Yahoo! and AOL agreed to a deal in which Microsoft's enterprise IM server Live Communications Server 2005 would have the possibility to talk to their rival counterparts and vice versa.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] On October 13, 2005, Microsoft and Yahoo! announced that their IM networks would soon be interoperable, using SIP/SIMPLE.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] This was finally rolled out to Windows Live Messenger and Yahoo!
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Additionally, in December 2005 by the AOL and Google strategic partnership deal, it was announced that AIM and ICQ users would be able to communicate with Google Talk users.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] However this feature took until December 2007 to roll out.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] XMPP provided the best example of open protocol interoperability, having had gateways that connected to Google Talk, Lotus Sametime and others.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Later, RCS was developed by telecommunication companies as an instant messaging protocol to replace SMS under a unified standard.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In 2022, the European Union passed the Digital Markets Act, which largely came into effect in early 2023.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Among other things, the legislation mandates certain interoperability between the largest IM platforms in use in Europe.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] As a result, in March 2024, Meta Platforms opened up its WhatsApp and Messenger networks to be interoperable.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Some approaches allow organizations to deploy their own, private instant messaging network by enabling them to restrict access to the server (often with the IM network entirely behind their firewall) and administer user permissions.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Other corporate messaging systems allow registered users to also connect from outside the corporation LAN, by using an encrypted, firewall-friendly, HTTPS-based protocol.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Usually, a dedicated corporate IM server has several advantages, such as pre-populated contact lists, integrated authentication, and better security and privacy.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging has changed how people communicate in the workplace.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Enterprise messaging applications like Slack, Symphony, Teamnote and Yammer allow companies to enforce policies on how employees message at work and ensure secure storage of sensitive data.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] They allow employees to separate work information from their personal emails and texts.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Messaging applications may make workplace communication efficient, but they can also have consequences on productivity.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] A study at Slack showed on average, people spend 10 hours a day on Slack, which is about 67% more time than they spend using email.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging is implemented in many video-conferencing tools.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] A study of chat use during work-related videoconferencing found that chat during meetings allows participants to communicate without interrupting the meeting, plan action around common resources, and enables greater inclusion.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The study also found that chat can cause distractions and information asymmetries between participants.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Users sometimes make use of internet slang or text speak to abbreviate common words or expressions to quicken conversations or reduce keystrokes.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The language has become widespread, with well-known expressions such as 'lol' translated over to face-to-face language.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Emotions are often expressed in shorthand, such as the abbreviation LOL, BRB and TTYL; respectively laugh(ing) out loud, be right back, and talk to you later.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Some, however, attempt to be more accurate with emotional expression over IM.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Real time reactions such as (*chortle*) (*snort*) (*guffaw*) or (*eye-roll*) have been popular at one point.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Also there are certain standards that are being introduced into mainstream conversations including, '#' indicates the use of sarcasm in a statement and '*' which indicates a spelling mistake and/or grammatical error in the prior message, followed by a correction.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messaging products can usually be categorised into two types: Enterprise Instant Messaging (EIM) and Consumer Instant Messaging (CIM).
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Enterprise solutions use an internal IM server, however this is not always feasible, particularly for smaller businesses with limited budgets.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The second option, using a CIM provides the advantage of being inexpensive to implement and has little need for investing in new hardware or server software.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] IM is increasingly becoming a feature of enterprise software rather than a stand-alone application.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Tens of millions of the consumer IM accounts in use are being used for business purposes by employees of companies and other organizations.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The adoption of IM across corporate networks outside of the control of IT organizations creates risks and liabilities for companies who do not effectively manage and support IM use.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] IM was initially shunned by the corporate world partly due to security concerns, but by 2003 many had started embracing these new services.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In response to the demand for business-grade IM and the need to ensure security and legal compliance, a new type of instant messaging, called "Enterprise Instant Messaging" ("EIM") was created when Lotus Development launched IBM Lotus Sametime in 1998.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Microsoft followed suit shortly thereafter with Microsoft Exchange Instant Messaging, later created a new platform called Microsoft Office Live Communications Server, and released Office Communications Server 2007 in October 2007.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Oracle Corporation also jumped into the market with its Oracle Beehive unified collaboration software.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Both IBM Lotus and Microsoft have introduced federation between their EIM systems and some of the public IM networks so that employees may use one interface to both their internal EIM system and their contacts on AOL, MSN, and Yahoo.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] As of 2010, leading EIM platforms include IBM Lotus Sametime, Microsoft Office Communications Server, Jabber XCP and Cisco Unified Presence.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Industry-focused EIM platforms such as Reuters Messaging and Bloomberg Messaging also provide IM abilities to financial services companies.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Crackers (malicious or black hat hackers) have consistently used IM networks as vectors for delivering phishing attempts, drive-by URLs, and virus-laden file attachments, with over 1100 discrete attacks listed by the IM Security Center in 2004–2007.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] IM connections sometimes occur in plain text, making them vulnerable to eavesdropping.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Also, IM client software often requires the user to expose open UDP ports to the world, raising the threat posed by potential security vulnerabilities.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In the early 2000s, a new class of IT security providers emerged to provide remedies for the risks and liabilities faced by corporations who chose to use IM for business communications.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The IM security providers created new products to be installed in corporate networks for the purpose of archiving, content-scanning, and security-scanning IM traffic moving in and out of the corporation.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Similar to the e-mail filtering vendors, the IM security providers focus on the risks and liabilities described above.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] With the rapid adoption of IM in the workplace, demand for IM security products began to grow in the mid-2000s.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] By 2007, the preferred platform for the purchase of security software had become the "computer appliance", according to IDC, who estimated that by 2008, 80% of network security products would be delivered via an appliance.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] By 2014, however, instant messengers' safety level was still extremely poor.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] According to a scorecard by the Electronic Frontier Foundation, only 7 out of 39 instant messengers received a perfect score.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In contrast, the most popular instant messengers at the time only attained a score of 2 out of 7.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] A number of studies have shown that IM services are quite vulnerable for providing user privacy.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In 2023, cybersecurity researchers discovered that numerous malicious "mods" exist of the Telegram instant messenger, which is freely available for download from Google Play.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Instant messages are often logged in a local message history, similar to emails' persistent nature.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] IM networks may store messages with either local-based device storage (e.g.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] WhatsApp, Viber, Line, WeChat, Signal etc. software) or cloud-based server storage provided by the service (e.g.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Telegram, Skype, Facebook Messenger, Google Meet/Chat, Discord, Slack etc.).
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Although cloud-based storage is advertised to offer encrypted messages, it poses an increased risk that the IM provider may have access to the decryption keys and view the user's saved messages.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] This requires users to trust IM servers and providers because messages can generally be accessed by the company.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Companies may be compelled to reveal their user's communication and suspend user accounts for any reason.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] News reports from 2013 revealed that the NSA is not only collecting emails and IM messages but also tracking relationships between senders and receivers of those chats and emails in a process known as metadata collection.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Metadata refers to the data concerned about the chat or email as opposed to contents of messages.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] It may be used to collect valuable information.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In January 2014, Matthew Campbell and Michael Hurley filed a class-action lawsuit against Facebook for breaching the Electronic Communications Privacy Act.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] They alleged that the information in their supposedly private messages was being read and used to generate profit, specifically "for purposes including but not limited to data mining and user profiling".
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In corporate use of IM, organizational offerings have become very sophisticated in their security and logging measures.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] An employee or organization member must be granted login credentials and permission to use the messaging system.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Creating a specific account for each user allows the organization to identify, track and record all use of their messenger system on their servers.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Encryption is the primary method that instant messaging apps use to protect user's data privacy and security.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] For corporate use, encryption and conversation archiving are usually regarded as important features due to security concerns.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] There are also a bunch of open source encrypting messengers.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] IM does hold potential advantages over SMS.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Current instant messaging networks that use end-to-end encryption include Signal, WhatsApp, Wire and iMessage.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Signal and iMessage have started using Post-quantum cryptography in September 2023 and April 2024 respectively.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Applications that have been criticized for lacking or poor encryption methods include Telegram and Confide, as both are prone to error or not having encryption enabled by default.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In addition to the malicious code threat, using instant messaging at work creates a risk of non-compliance with laws and regulations governing electronic communications in businesses.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] In the United States alone, there are over 10,000 laws and regulations related to electronic messaging and records retention.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The better-known of these include the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, HIPAA, and SEC 17a-3.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Changes to Federal Rules of Civil Procedure, effective December 1, 2006, created a new category for electronic records which may be requested during discovery in legal proceedings.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Most nations also regulate electronic messaging and records retention similarly to the United States.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] The most common regulations related to IM at work involve producing archived business communications to satisfy government or judicial requests under law.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] Many instant messaging communications fall into the category of business communications that must be archived and retrievable.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] There are 25 countries in the world where WhatsApp messenger is not the market leader in IM, such as the United States, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Denmark, Norway, Sweden, Hungary, Lithuania, Poland, Slovakia, Philippines, and China.
[src:sip-protocol/instant-messaging] IM apps have varying levels of adoption in different countries.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-communication] Hard real-time communication systems are frequently electromechanically linked to a physical mechanism, often one that interfaces directly with people or property, which often contributes to or defines the potential danger of a fault.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-communication] Due to their safety-critical nature, the communication protocols defined in a hard real-time system generally must be deterministic.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-communication] Hard real-time communication systems are particularly common in the transportation, industrial, and medical sectors.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-communication] Common applications include control systems, automotive controllers, medical devices, and critical safety systems such as airbag firing computers.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-communication] Unlike hard real-time communication systems, soft real-time communication systems generally do not have the capacity to cause catastrophic harm upon a fault, which allows for non-deterministic, less rigorous network infrastructure.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-communication] This allows soft real-time communication systems to operate over consumer networks such as residential internet connections and cellular networks.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-communication] A large amount of soft real-time systems are telecommunications products such as VoIP systems and certain video calling platforms such as Discord and Google Meet.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-communication] Data transmitted over a soft real-time communication system is not stored in a centralized server, and peers are connected directly to one another rather than through a server, although intermediary connecting nodes between peers are allowed when a direct link cannot be established.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The **Real-time Transport Protocol** (**RTP**) is a network protocol for delivering audio and video over IP networks.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used in communication and entertainment systems that involve streaming media, such as telephony, video teleconference applications including WebRTC, television services and web-based push-to-talk features.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP typically runs over User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used in conjunction with the RTP Control Protocol (RTCP).
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] While RTP carries the media streams (e.g., audio and video), RTCP is used to monitor transmission statistics and quality of service (QoS) and aids synchronization of multiple streams.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is one of the technical foundations of voice over IP and in this context is often used in conjunction with a signaling protocol such as the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), which establishes connections across the network.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP was developed by the Audio-Video Transport Working Group of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and first published in 1996 as RFC 1889, which was then superseded by RFC 3550 in 2003.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Research on audio and video over packet-switched networks dates back to the early 1970s.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) published RFC 741 in 1977 and began developing RTP in 1992, and would go on to develop Session Announcement Protocol (SAP), the Session Description Protocol (SDP), and the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP).
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is designed for end-to-end, real-time transfer of streaming media.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The protocol provides facilities for jitter compensation and detection of packet loss and out-of-order delivery, which are common, especially during UDP transmissions on an IP network.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP allows data transfer to multiple destinations through IP multicast.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is regarded as the primary standard for audio/video transport in IP networks and is used with an associated profile and payload format.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The design of RTP is based on the architectural principle known as application-layer framing, where protocol functions are implemented in the application as opposed to the operating system's protocol stack.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Real-time multimedia streaming applications require timely delivery of information and often can tolerate some packet loss to achieve this goal.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] For example, loss of a packet in an audio application may result in loss of a fraction of a second of audio data, which can be made unnoticeable with suitable error concealment algorithms.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), although standardized for RTP use, is not normally used in RTP applications because TCP favors reliability over timeliness.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Instead, the majority of the RTP implementations are built on the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Other transport protocols specifically designed for multimedia sessions are SCTP and DCCP, although, as of 2012, they were not in widespread use.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP was developed by the Audio/Video Transport working group of the IETF standards organization.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used in conjunction with other protocols such as H.323 and RTSP.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP specification describes two protocols: RTP and RTCP.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used for the transfer of multimedia data, and the RTCP is used to periodically send control information and QoS parameters.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The data transfer protocol, RTP, carries real-time data.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Information provided by this protocol includes timestamps (for synchronization), sequence numbers (for packet loss and reordering detection) and the payload format, which indicates the encoded format of the data.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The control protocol, RTCP, is used for quality of service (QoS) feedback and synchronization between the media streams.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The bandwidth of RTCP traffic compared to RTP is small, typically around 5%.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP sessions are typically initiated between communicating peers using a signaling protocol, such as H.323, the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), RTSP, or Jingle (XMPP).
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] These protocols may use the Session Description Protocol to specify the parameters for the sessions.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] An RTP session is established for each multimedia stream.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Audio and video streams may use separate RTP sessions, enabling a receiver to selectively receive components of a particular stream.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP and RTCP design is independent of the transport protocol.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Applications most typically use UDP with port numbers in the unprivileged range (1024 to 65535).
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP) may be used when a reliable transport protocol is desired.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP specification recommends even port numbers for RTP and the use of the next odd port number for the associated RTCP session.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] A single port can be used for RTP and RTCP in applications that multiplex the protocols.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used by real-time multimedia applications such as voice over IP, audio over IP, WebRTC, Internet Protocol television, and professional video over IP including SMPTE 2022 and SMPTE 2110.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is designed to carry a multitude of multimedia formats, which permits the development of new formats without revising the RTP standard.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] To this end, the information required by a specific application of the protocol is not included in the generic RTP header.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] For each class of application (e.g., audio, video), RTP defines a *profile* and associated *payload formats*.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Every instantiation of RTP in a particular application requires a profile and payload format specifications.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The profile defines the codecs used to encode the payload data and their mapping to payload format codes in the protocol field *Payload Type* (PT) of the RTP header.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Each profile is accompanied by several payload format specifications, each of which describes the transport of particular encoded data.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The mapping of MPEG-4 audio/video streams to RTP packets is specified in RFC 3016, and H.263 video payloads are described in RFC 2429.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP packets are created at the application layer and handed to the transport layer for delivery.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Each unit of RTP media data created by an application begins with the RTP packet header.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP header has a minimum size of 12 bytes.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] After the header, optional header extensions may be present.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] This is followed by the RTP payload, the format of which is determined by the particular class of application.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Used to indicate if there are extra padding bytes at the end of the RTP packet.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Padding may be used to fill up a block of certain size, for example, as required by an encryption algorithm.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The last byte of the padding contains the number of padding bytes that were added (including itself).
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The extension header is application or profile specific.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Contains the number of CSRC identifiers (defined below) that follow the SSRC (also defined below).
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Signaling used at the application level in a profile-specific manner.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] If it is set, it means that the current data has some special relevance for the application.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Indicates the format of the payload and thus determines its interpretation by the application.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Values are profile specific and may be dynamically assigned.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Used by the receiver to play back the received samples at appropriate time and interval.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] When several media streams are present, the timestamps may be independent in each stream.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The granularity of the timing is application specific.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] For example, an audio application that samples data once every 125 μs (8 kHz, a common sample rate in digital telephony) would use that value as its clock resolution.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Video streams typically use a 90 kHz clock.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The clock granularity is one of the details that is specified in the RTP profile for an application.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] uniquely identifies the source of a stream.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The synchronization sources within the same RTP session will be unique.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] enumerate contributing sources to a stream that has been generated from multiple sources.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] indicates the length of the extension in 32-bit units, excluding the 32 bits of the extension header.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] A functional multimedia application requires other protocols and standards used in conjunction with RTP.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Protocols such as SIP, Jingle, RTSP, H.225 and H.245 are used for session initiation, control and termination.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] Other standards, such as H.264, MPEG and H.263, are used for encoding the payload data as specified by the applicable RTP profile.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] An RTP sender captures the multimedia data, then encodes, frames and transmits it as RTP packets with appropriate timestamps and increasing timestamps and sequence numbers.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The sender sets the *payload type* field in accordance with connection negotiation and the RTP profile in use.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP receiver detects missing packets and may reorder packets.
[src:sip-protocol/real-time-transport-protocol] It decodes the media data in the packets according to the payload type and presents the stream to its user.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] The **Session Description Protocol** (**SDP**) is a format for describing multimedia communication sessions for the purposes of announcement and invitation.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Its predominant use is in support of streaming media applications, such as voice over IP (VoIP) and video conferencing.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] SDP does not deliver any media streams itself but is used between endpoints for negotiation of network metrics, media types, and other associated properties.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] The set of properties and parameters is called a *session profile*.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] SDP is extensible for the support of new media types and formats.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] SDP was originally a component of the Session Announcement Protocol (SAP), but found other uses in conjunction with the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP), the Real-time Streaming Protocol (RTSP), Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), and as a standalone protocol for describing multicast sessions.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] The IETF published the original specification as a Proposed Standard in April 1998 (RFC 2327).
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Revised specifications were released in 2006 (RFC 4566), and in 2021 (RFC 8866).
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] The Session Description Protocol describes a session as a group of fields in a text-based format, one field per line.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Where `<character>` is a single case-sensitive character and `<value>` is structured text in a format that depends on the character.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed immediately to either side of the equal sign.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Session descriptions consist of three sections: session, timing, and media descriptions.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Each description may contain multiple timing and media descriptions.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Names are only unique within the associated syntactic construct.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Below is a sample session description from RFC 4566.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] This session is originated by the user "jdoe", at IPv4 address 10.47.16.5.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Its name is "SDP Seminar" and extended session information ("A Seminar on the session description protocol") is included along with a link for additional information and an email address to contact the responsible party, Jane Doe.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] This session is specified to last for two hours using NTP timestamps, with a connection address (which indicates the address clients must connect to or — when a multicast address is provided, as it is here — subscribe to) specified as IPv4 224.2.17.12 with a TTL of 127.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Recipients of this session description are instructed to only receive media.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Two media descriptions are provided, both using RTP Audio Video Profile.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] The first is an audio stream on port 49170 using RTP/AVP payload type 0 (defined by RFC 3551 as PCMU), and the second is a video stream on port 51372 using RTP/AVP payload type 99 (defined as "dynamic").
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Finally, an attribute is included which maps RTP/AVP payload type 99 to format h263-1998 with a 90 kHz clock rate.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] RTCP ports for the audio and video streams of 49171 and 51373, respectively, are implied.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] The SDP specification is purely a format for session description.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] It is intended to be distributed over different transport protocols as necessary, including SAP, SIP, and RTSP.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] SDP could even be transmitted by email or as an HTTP payload.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] SDP uses attributes to extend the core protocol.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Attributes can appear within the Session or Media sections and are scoped accordingly as *session-level* or *media-level*.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] New attributes are added to the standard occasionally through registration with IANA.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] The parameters *v*, *s*, and *o* are mandatory, must not be empty, and should be UTF-8-encoded.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] They are used as identifiers and are not intended to be displayed to users.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] A few other attributes are also present in the example, either as a session-level attribute (such as the attribute in property form *a=recvonly*), or as a media-level attribute (such as the attribute in value form *a=rtpmap:99 h263-1998/90000* for the video in the example).
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Absolute times are represented in Network Time Protocol (NTP) format (the number of seconds since 1900).
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] If the stop time is 0 then the session is *unbounded*.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] If the start time is also zero then the session is considered *permanent*.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Unbounded and permanent sessions are discouraged but not prohibited.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Intervals can be represented with NTP times or in typed time: a value and time units (days: *d*, hours: *h*, minutes: *m* and seconds: *s*) sequence.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] When repeat times are specified, the start time of each repetition may need to be adjusted to compensate for daylight saving time changes so that it will occur at the same local time in a specific time zone throughout the period between the start time and the stop time.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] All these offsets are relative to the start time, they are not cumulative.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] NTP supports this with field *z*, which indicates a series of pairs whose first item is the NTP absolute time when a daylight adjustment will occur, and the second item indicates the offset to apply relative to the absolute times computed with the field *r*.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] For example, if a daylight adjustment will subtract 1 hour on 31 October 2010 at 3 am UTC (i.e.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] If the weekly 1-hour session was repeated every Sunday for one full year, i.e. from Sunday 1 August 2010 3 am UTC to Sunday 26 June 2011 4 am UTC (stop time of the last repeat, i.e.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] As SDP announcements for repeated sessions should not be made to cover very long periods exceeding a few years, the number of daylight adjustments to include in the z= parameter should remain small.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] Sessions may be repeated irregularly over a week but scheduled the same way for all weeks in the period, by adding more tuples in the *r* parameter.
[src:sip-protocol/session-description-protocol] The SDP protocol does not support repeating sessions monthly and yearly schedules with such simple repeat times, because they are irregularly spaced in time; instead, additional *t*/*r* tuples may be supplied for each month or year.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The **Session Initiation Protocol** (**SIP**) is a signaling protocol used for initiating, maintaining, modifying, and terminating communication sessions that involve multimedia elements such as voice, video, and messaging.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] It operates at the application layer of the Internet protocol suite and is widely used in Internet telephony, private IP-based telephone systems, and mobile communication over LTE networks through VoLTE.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is a text-based protocol modeled on the structure of HTTP and SMTP, enabling interoperability and integration with other Internet applications.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] It provides mechanisms for user location, session setup, and session management, making it a foundational component of modern IP multimedia systems.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The protocol defines the specific format of messages exchanged and the sequence of communications for cooperation of the participants.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is a text-based protocol, incorporating many elements of the Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) and the Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] A call established with SIP may consist of multiple media streams, but no separate streams are required for applications, such as text messaging, that exchange data as payload in the SIP message.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP works in conjunction with several other protocols that specify and carry the session media.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Most commonly, media type and parameter negotiation and media setup are performed with the Session Description Protocol (SDP), which is carried as payload in SIP messages.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is designed to be independent of the underlying transport layer protocol and can be used with the User Datagram Protocol (UDP), the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), and the Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] For secure transmissions of SIP messages over insecure network links, the protocol may be encrypted with Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] For the transmission of media streams (voice, video) the SDP payload carried in SIP messages typically employs the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) or the Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP was originally designed by Mark Handley, Henning Schulzrinne, Eve Schooler and Jonathan Rosenberg in 1996 to facilitate establishing multicast multimedia sessions on the Mbone.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The protocol was standardized as RFC 2543 in 1999.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] In November 2000, SIP was accepted as a 3GPP signaling protocol and permanent element of the IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS) architecture for IP-based streaming multimedia services in cellular networks.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] In June 2002 the specification was revised in RFC 3261 and various extensions and clarifications have been published since.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP was designed to provide a signaling and call setup protocol for IP-based communications supporting the call processing functions and features present in the public switched telephone network (PSTN) with a vision of supporting new multimedia applications.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] It has been extended for video conferencing, streaming media distribution, instant messaging, presence information, file transfer, Internet fax and online games.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is distinguished by its proponents for having roots in the Internet community rather than in the telecommunications industry.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP has been standardized primarily by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF), while other protocols, such as H.323, have traditionally been associated with the International Telecommunication Union (ITU).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is only involved in the signaling operations of a media communication session and is primarily used to set up and terminate voice or video calls.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP can be used to establish two-party (unicast) or multiparty (multicast) sessions.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] It also allows modification of existing calls.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The modification can involve changing addresses or ports, inviting more participants, and adding or deleting media streams.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP has also found applications in messaging applications, such as instant messaging, and event subscription and notification.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP works in conjunction with several other protocols that specify the media format and coding and that carry the media once the call is set up.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] For call setup, the body of a SIP message contains a Session Description Protocol (SDP) data unit, which specifies the media format, codec and media communication protocol.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Voice and video media streams are typically carried between the terminals using the Real-time Transport Protocol (RTP) or Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Every resource of a SIP network, such as user agents, call routers, and voicemail boxes, are identified by a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The syntax of the URI follows the general standard syntax also used in Web services and e-mail.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The URI scheme used for SIP is *sip* and a typical SIP URI has the form *sip:username@domainname* or *sip:username@hostport*, where *domainname* requires DNS SRV records to locate the servers for SIP domain while *hostport* can be an IP address or a fully qualified domain name of the host and port.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] If secure transmission is required, the scheme *sips* is used.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP employs design elements similar to the HTTP request and response transaction model.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Each transaction consists of a client request that invokes a particular method or function on the server and at least one response.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP reuses most of the header fields, encoding rules and status codes of HTTP, providing a readable text-based format.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP can be carried by several transport layer protocols including Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), User Datagram Protocol (UDP), and Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP clients typically use TCP or UDP on port numbers 5060 or 5061 for SIP traffic to servers and other endpoints.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Port 5060 is commonly used for non-encrypted signaling traffic whereas port 5061 is typically used for traffic encrypted with Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP-based telephony networks often implement call processing features of Signaling System 7 (SS7), for which special SIP protocol extensions exist, although the two protocols themselves are very different.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SS7 is a centralized protocol, characterized by a complex central network architecture and dumb endpoints (traditional telephone handsets).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is a client-server protocol of equipotent peers.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP features are implemented in the communicating endpoints, while the traditional SS7 architecture is in use only between switching centers.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The network elements that use the Session Initiation Protocol for communication are called *SIP user agents*.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Each *user agent* (UA) performs the function of a *user agent client* (UAC) when it is requesting a service function, and that of a *user agent server* (UAS) when responding to a request.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Thus, any two SIP endpoints may in principle operate without any intervening SIP infrastructure.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] However, for network operational reasons, for provisioning public services to users, and for directory services, SIP defines several specific types of network server elements.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Each of these service elements also communicates within the client-server model implemented in user agent clients and servers.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] A user agent is a logical network endpoint that sends or receives SIP messages and manages SIP sessions.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] User agents have client and server components.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The user agent client (UAC) sends SIP requests.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The user agent server (UAS) receives requests and returns a SIP response.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Unlike other network protocols that fix the roles of client and server, e.g., in HTTP, in which a web browser only acts as a client, and never as a server, SIP requires both peers to implement both roles.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The roles of UAC and UAS only last for the duration of a SIP transaction.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] A SIP phone is an IP phone that implements client and server functions of a SIP user agent and provides the traditional call functions of a telephone, such as dial, answer, reject, call hold, and call transfer.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP phones may be implemented as a hardware device or as a softphone.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] As vendors increasingly implement SIP as a standard telephony platform, the distinction between hardware-based and software-based SIP phones is blurred and SIP elements are implemented in the basic firmware functions of many IP-capable communications devices such as smartphones.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] In SIP, as in HTTP, the user agent may identify itself using a message header field (*User-Agent*), containing a text description of the software, hardware, or the product name.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The user agent field is sent in request messages, which means that the receiving SIP server can evaluate this information to perform device-specific configuration or feature activation.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Operators of SIP network elements sometimes store this information in customer account portals, where it can be useful in diagnosing SIP compatibility problems or in the display of service status.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] A proxy server is a network server with UAC and UAS components that functions as an intermediary entity for the purpose of performing requests on behalf of other network elements.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] A proxy server primarily plays the role of call routing; it sends SIP requests to another entity closer to the destination.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Proxies are also useful for enforcing policy, such as for determining whether a user is allowed to make a call.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] A proxy interprets, and, if necessary, rewrites specific parts of a request message before forwarding it.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP proxy servers that route messages to more than one destination are called forking proxies.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The forking of a SIP request establishes multiple dialogs from the single request.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Thus, a call may be answered from one of multiple SIP endpoints.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] For identification of multiple dialogs, each dialog has an identifier with contributions from both endpoints.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] A redirect server is a user agent server that generates 3xx (redirection) responses to requests it receives, directing the client to contact an alternate set of URIs.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] A redirect server allows proxy servers to direct SIP session invitations to external domains.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] A registrar is a SIP endpoint that provides a location service.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] It accepts REGISTER requests, recording the address and other parameters from the user agent.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] For subsequent requests, it provides an essential means to locate possible communication peers on the network.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The location service links one or more IP addresses to the SIP URI of the registering agent.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Multiple user agents may register for the same URI, with the result that all registered user agents receive the calls to the URI.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP registrars are logical elements and are often co-located with SIP proxies.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] To improve network scalability, location services may instead be located with a redirect server.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Session border controllers (SBCs) serve as middleboxes between user agents and SIP servers for various types of functions, including network topology hiding and assistance in NAT traversal.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SBCs are an independently engineered solution and are not mentioned in the SIP RFC.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Gateways can be used to interconnect a SIP network to other networks, such as the PSTN, which use different protocols or technologies.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is a text-based protocol with syntax similar to that of HTTP.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] There are two different types of SIP messages: requests and responses.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The first line of a request has a *method*, defining the nature of the request, and a Request-URI, indicating where the request should be sent.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The first line of a response has a *response code*.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Requests initiate a functionality of the protocol.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] They are sent by a user agent client to the server and are answered with one or more SIP responses, which return a result code of the transaction, and generally indicate the success, failure, or other state of the transaction.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Responses are sent by the user agent server indicating the result of a received request.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP defines a transaction mechanism to control the exchanges between participants and deliver messages reliably.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] A transaction is a state of a session, which is controlled by various timers.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Client transactions send requests and server transactions respond to those requests with one or more responses.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The responses may include provisional responses with a response code in the form *1xx*, and one or multiple final responses (2xx – 6xx).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Transactions are further categorized as either type *invite* or type *non-invite*.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Invite transactions differ in that they can establish a long-running conversation, referred to as a *dialog* in SIP, and so include an acknowledgment (ACK) of any non-failing final response, e.g., *200 OK*.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The Session Initiation Protocol for Instant Messaging and Presence Leveraging Extensions (SIMPLE) is the SIP-based suite of standards for instant messaging and presence information.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Message Session Relay Protocol (MSRP) allows instant message sessions and file transfer.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The SIP developer community meets regularly at conferences organized by SIP Forum to test interoperability of SIP implementations.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The TTCN-3 test specification language, developed by a task force at ETSI (STF 196), is used for specifying conformance tests for SIP implementations.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] When developing SIP software or deploying a new SIP infrastructure, it is important to test the capability of servers and IP networks to handle certain call load: number of concurrent calls and number of calls per second.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP performance tester software is used to simulate SIP and RTP traffic to see if the server and IP network are stable under the call load.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The software measures performance indicators like answer delay, answer/seizure ratio, RTP jitter and packet loss, round-trip delay time.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP trunking is a similar marketing term preferred for when the service is used to simplify a telecom infrastructure by sharing the carrier access circuit for voice, data, and Internet traffic while removing the need for PRI circuits.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP-enabled video surveillance cameras can initiate calls to alert the operator of events, such as the motion of objects in a protected area.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP is used in audio over IP for broadcasting applications where it provides an interoperable means for audio interfaces from different manufacturers to make connections with one another.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST), Advanced Networking Technologies Division provides a public-domain Java implementation that serves as a reference implementation for the standard.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The implementation can work in proxy server or user agent scenarios and has been used in numerous commercial and research projects.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] It supports RFC 3261 in full and a number of extension RFCs including RFC 6665 (event notification) and RFC 3262 (reliable provisional responses).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Numerous other commercial and open-source SIP implementations exist.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP-I, Session Initiation Protocol with encapsulated ISUP, is a protocol used to create, modify, and terminate communication sessions based on ISUP using SIP and IP networks.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Services using SIP-I include voice, video telephony, fax and data.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP-I and SIP-T are two protocols with similar features, notably to allow ISUP messages to be transported over SIP networks.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] This preserves all of the detail available in the ISUP header.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIP-I was defined by the ITU-T, whereas SIP-T was defined by the IETF.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] Concerns about the security of calls via the public Internet have been addressed by encryption of the SIP protocol for secure transmission.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The URI scheme SIPS is used to mandate that SIP communication be secured with Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] SIPS URIs take the form sips:user@example.com.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] End-to-end encryption of SIP is only possible if there is a direct connection between communication endpoints.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] While a direct connection can be made via Peer-to-peer SIP or via a VPN between the endpoints, most SIP communication involves multiple hops, with the first hop being from a user agent to the user agent's ITSP.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] For the multiple-hop case, SIPS will only secure the first hop; the remaining hops will normally not be secured with TLS and the SIP communication will be insecure.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] In contrast, the HTTPS protocol provides end-to-end security as it is done with a direct connection and does not involve the notion of hops.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The media streams (audio and video), which are separate connections from the SIPS signaling stream, may be encrypted using SRTP.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] The key exchange for SRTP is performed with SDES (RFC 4568), or with ZRTP (RFC 6189).
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] When SDES is used, the keys will be transmitted via insecure SIP unless SIPS is used.
[src:sip-protocol/session-initiation-protocol] One may also add a MIKEY (RFC 3830) exchange to SIP to determine session keys for use with SRTP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has evolved to integrate with mobile telephony, including Voice over LTE (VoLTE) and Voice over NR (Vo5G), enabling seamless voice communication over mobile data networks.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] These advancements have extended VoIP's role beyond its traditional use in Internet-based applications.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] It has become a key component of modern mobile infrastructure, as 4G and 5G networks rely entirely on this technology for voice transmission.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The steps and principles involved in originating VoIP telephone calls are similar to traditional digital telephony and involve signaling, channel setup, digitization of the analog voice signals, and encoding.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Instead of being transmitted over a circuit-switched network, the digital information is packetized and transmission occurs as IP packets over a packet-switched network.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] They transport media streams using special media delivery protocols that encode audio and video with audio codecs and video codecs.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Various codecs exist that optimize the media stream based on application requirements and network bandwidth; some implementations rely on narrowband and compressed speech, while others support high-fidelity stereo codecs.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The most widely used speech coding standards in VoIP are based on the linear predictive coding (LPC) and modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) compression methods.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Popular codecs include the MDCT-based AAC-LD (used in FaceTime), the LPC/MDCT-based Opus (used in WhatsApp), the LPC-based SILK (used in Skype), μ-law, A-law versions of G.711, G.722, an open source voice codec known as iLBC, and a codec that uses only 8 kbit/s each way called G.729.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Early providers of voice-over-IP services used business models and offered technical solutions that mirrored the architecture of the legacy telephone network.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Second-generation providers, such as Skype, built closed networks for private user bases, offering the benefit of free calls and convenience while potentially charging for access to other communication networks, such as the PSTN.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This limited the freedom of users to mix-and-match third-party hardware and software.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Third-generation providers, such as Google Talk, adopted the concept of federated VoIP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] These solutions typically allow dynamic interconnection between users in any two domains of the Internet, when a user wishes to place a call.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In addition to VoIP phones, VoIP is also available on many personal computers and other Internet access devices.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Calls and SMS text messages may be sent via Wi-Fi or the carrier's mobile data network.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP provides a framework for consolidation of all modern communications technologies using a single unified communications system.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has been adapted for use in mobile networks, leading to the development of advanced systems designed to support voice communication over modern data infrastructures.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Among these are Voice over LTE (VoLTE) and Voice over 5G (Vo5G), which enable voice communication over IP-based mobile infrastructures.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In contrast to traditional VoIP services, which often function independently of global telephone numbering systems, VoLTE and Vo5G are directly connected to mobile operators' infrastructures, providing seamless connectivity to the international telephone network.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoLTE, introduced as part of 4G LTE networks, enables voice communication over an IP-based infrastructure initially developed for data transmission.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] It offers features such as high-definition voice (HD Voice) and faster call setup times compared to circuit-switched networks.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Vo5G, the 5G equivalent of VoLTE, utilizes the increased speed, reduced latency, and greater capacity of 5G networks to further enhance these capabilities.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Both VoLTE and Vo5G maintain compatibility with traditional public switched telephone networks (PSTNs), allowing users to make and receive calls to and from any telephone number worldwide.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] These technologies differ from standalone VoIP services by being fully integrated with mobile network operators.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This integration ensures additional features such as emergency call support and quality-of-service guarantees, making them a central part of modern mobile telecommunication systems.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice over IP has been implemented with proprietary protocols and protocols based on open standards in applications such as VoIP phones, mobile applications, and web-based communications.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A variety of functions are needed to implement VoIP communication.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Some protocols perform multiple functions, while others perform only a few and must be used in concert.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Mass-market VoIP services use existing broadband Internet access, by which subscribers place and receive telephone calls in much the same manner as they would via the PSTN.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Full-service VoIP phone companies provide inbound and outbound service with direct inbound dialing.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Many offer unlimited domestic calling and sometimes international calls for a flat monthly subscription fee.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Phone calls between subscribers of the same provider are usually free when flat-fee service is not available.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A VoIP phone is necessary to connect to a VoIP service provider.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] It is increasingly common for telecommunications providers to use VoIP telephony over dedicated and public IP networks as a backhaul to connect switching centers and to interconnect with other telephony network providers; this is often referred to as *IP backhaul*.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Smartphones may have SIP clients built into the firmware or available as an application download.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Because of the bandwidth efficiency and low costs that VoIP technology can provide, businesses are migrating from traditional copper-wire telephone systems to VoIP systems to reduce their monthly phone costs.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In 2008, 80% of all new Private branch exchange (PBX) lines installed internationally were VoIP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, in the United States, the Social Security Administration is converting its field offices of 63,000 workers from traditional phone installations to a VoIP infrastructure carried over its existing data network.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP allows both voice and data communications to be run over a single network, which can significantly reduce infrastructure costs.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The prices of extensions on VoIP are lower than for PBX and key systems.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP switches may run on commodity hardware, such as personal computers.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Rather than closed architectures, these devices rely on standard interfaces.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP devices have simple, intuitive user interfaces, so users can often make simple system configuration changes.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Dual-mode phones enable users to continue their conversations as they move between an outside cellular service and an internal Wi-Fi network, so that it is no longer necessary to carry both a desktop phone and a cell phone.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Maintenance becomes simpler as there are fewer devices to oversee.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP solutions aimed at businesses have evolved into unified communications services that treat all communications—phone calls, faxes, voice mail, e-mail, web conferences, and more—as discrete units that can all be delivered via any means and to any handset, including cellphones.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Two kinds of service providers are operating in this space: one set is focused on VoIP for medium to large enterprises, while another is targeting the small-to-medium business (SMB) market.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Skype, which originally marketed itself as a service among friends, began to cater to businesses in 2009, providing free-of-charge connections between any users on the Skype network and connecting to and from ordinary PSTN telephones for a charge.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In general, the provision of VoIP telephony systems to organizational or individual users can be divided into two primary delivery methods: private or on-premises solutions, or externally hosted solutions delivered by third-party providers.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] On-premises delivery methods are more akin to the classic PBX deployment model for connecting an office to local PSTN networks.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] While many use cases still remain for private or on-premises VoIP systems, the wider market has been gradually shifting toward *Cloud* or *Hosted* VoIP solutions.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Hosted systems are also generally better suited to smaller or personal use VoIP deployments, where a private system may not be viable for these scenarios.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Typically, this will be one or more data centers with geographic relevance to the end-user(s) of the system.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This infrastructure is external to the user of the system and is deployed and maintained by the service provider.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Endpoints, such as VoIP telephones or softphone applications (apps running on a computer or mobile device), will connect to the VoIP service remotely.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] These connections typically take place over public internet links, such as local fixed WAN breakout or mobile carrier service.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In the case of a private VoIP system, the primary telephony system itself is located within the private infrastructure of the end-user organization.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Usually, the system will be deployed on-premises at a site within the direct control of the organization.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This can provide numerous benefits in terms of QoS control (see below), cost scalability, and ensuring privacy and security of communications traffic.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] However, the responsibility for ensuring that the VoIP system remains performant and resilient is predominantly vested in the end-user organization.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This is not the case with a Hosted VoIP solution.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Private VoIP systems can be physical hardware PBX appliances, converged with other infrastructure, or they can be deployed as software applications.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Generally, the latter two options will be in the form of a separate virtualized appliance.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] However, in some scenarios, these systems are deployed on bare metal infrastructure or IoT devices.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] With some solutions, such as 3CX, companies can attempt to blend the benefits of hosted and private on-premises systems by implementing their own private solution but within an external environment.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Examples can include data center collocation services, public cloud, or private cloud locations.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] For on-premises systems, local endpoints within the same location typically connect directly over the LAN.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] For remote and external endpoints, available connectivity options mirror those of Hosted or Cloud VoIP solutions.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] However, VoIP traffic to and from the on-premises systems can often also be sent over secure private links.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Examples include personal VPN, site-to-site VPN, private networks such as MPLS and SD-WAN, or via private SBCs (Session Border Controllers).
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] While exceptions and private peering options do exist, it is generally uncommon for those private connectivity methods to be provided by Hosted or Cloud VoIP providers.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Communication on the IP network is perceived as less reliable in contrast to the circuit-switched public telephone network because it does not provide a network-based mechanism to ensure that data packets are not lost, and are delivered in sequential order.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] It is a best-effort network without fundamental quality of service (QoS) guarantees.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice, and all other data, travels in packets over IP networks with fixed maximum capacity.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Therefore, VoIP implementations may face problems with latency, packet loss, and jitter.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] By default, network routers handle traffic on a first-come, first-served basis.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Fixed delays cannot be controlled as they are caused by the physical distance the packets travel.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] They are especially problematic when satellite circuits are involved because of the long distance to a geostationary satellite and back; delays of 400–600 ms are typical.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Latency can be minimized by marking voice packets as being delay-sensitive with QoS methods such as DiffServ.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Network routers on high-volume traffic links may introduce latency that exceeds permissible thresholds for VoIP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Excessive load on a link can cause congestion and associated queueing delays and packet loss.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This signals a transport protocol like TCP to reduce its transmission rate to alleviate the congestion.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] But VoIP usually uses UDP, not TCP, because recovering from congestion through retransmission usually entails too much latency.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] So QoS mechanisms can avoid the undesirable loss of VoIP packets by immediately transmitting them ahead of any queued bulk traffic on the same link, even when the link is congested by bulk traffic.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP endpoints usually have to wait for the completion of transmission of previous packets before new data may be sent.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Although it is possible to preempt (abort) a less important packet in mid-transmission, this is not commonly done, especially on high-speed links where transmission times are short even for maximum-sized packets.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] An alternative to preemption on slower links, such as dialup and digital subscriber line (DSL), is to reduce the maximum transmission time by reducing the maximum transmission unit.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] But since every packet must contain protocol headers, this increases relative header overhead on every link traversed.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The receiver must resequence IP packets that arrive out of order and recover gracefully when packets arrive too late or not at all.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Packet delay variation results from changes in queuing delay along a given network path due to competition from other users for the same transmission links.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP receivers accommodate this variation by storing incoming packets briefly in a playout buffer, deliberately increasing latency to improve the chance that each packet will be on hand when it is time for the voice engine to play it.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The added delay is thus a compromise between excessive latency and excessive dropout, i.e., momentary audio interruptions.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Although jitter is a random variable, it is the sum of several other random variables that are at least somewhat independent: the individual queuing delays of the routers along the Internet path in question.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Motivated by the central limit theorem, jitter can be modeled as a Gaussian random variable.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This suggests continually estimating the mean delay and its standard deviation and setting the playout delay so that only packets delayed more than several standard deviations above the mean will arrive too late to be useful.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In practice, the variance in latency of many Internet paths is dominated by a small number (often one) of relatively slow and congested bottleneck links.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Most Internet backbone links are now so fast (e.g., 10 Gbit/s) that their delays are dominated by the transmission medium (e.g., optical fiber) and the routers driving them do not have enough buffering for queuing delays to be significant.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A number of protocols have been defined to support the reporting of quality of service (QoS) and quality of experience (QoE) for VoIP calls.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] These include RTP Control Protocol (RTCP) extended reports, SIP RTCP summary reports, H.460.9 Annex B (for H.323), H.248.30 and MGCP extensions.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP metrics reports are exchanged between IP endpoints on an occasional basis during a call, and an end-of-call message is sent via SIP RTCP summary report or one of the other signaling protocol extensions.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP metrics reports are intended to support real-time feedback related to QoS problems, the exchange of information between the endpoints for improved call quality calculation and a variety of other applications.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] DSL modems typically provide Ethernet connections to local equipment, but inside they may actually be Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) modems.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] They use ATM Adaptation Layer 5 (AAL5) to segment each Ethernet packet into a series of 53-byte ATM cells for transmission, reassembling them back into Ethernet frames at the receiving end.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Using a separate virtual circuit identifier (VCI) for voice over IP has the potential to reduce latency on shared connections.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] ATM's potential for latency reduction is greatest on slow links because worst-case latency decreases with increasing link speed.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A full-size (1500 byte) Ethernet frame takes 94 ms to transmit at 128 kbit/s but only 8 ms at 1.5 Mbit/s.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] If this is the bottleneck link, this latency is probably small enough to ensure good VoIP performance without MTU reductions or multiple ATM VCs.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The latest generations of DSL, VDSL and VDSL2, carry Ethernet without intermediate ATM/AAL5 layers, and they generally support IEEE 802.1p priority tagging so that VoIP can be queued ahead of less time-critical traffic.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] ATM has substantial header overhead: 5/53 = 9.4%, roughly twice the total header overhead of a 1500-byte Ethernet frame.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This *ATM tax* is incurred by every DSL user, whether or not they take advantage of multiple virtual circuits – and few can.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Several protocols are used in the data link layer and physical layer for quality-of-service mechanisms that help VoIP applications work well even in the presence of network congestion.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The quality of voice transmission is characterized by several metrics that may be monitored by network elements and by the user agent hardware or software.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Such metrics include network packet loss, packet jitter, packet latency (delay), post-dial delay, and echo.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The metrics are determined by VoIP performance testing and monitoring.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A VoIP media gateway controller (aka Class 5 Softswitch) works in cooperation with a media gateway (aka IP Business Gateway) and connects the digital media stream, so as to complete the path for voice and data.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Gateways include interfaces for connecting to standard PSTN networks.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Ethernet interfaces are also included in modern systems, which are specially designed to link calls that are passed via VoIP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] E.164 is a global numbering standard for both the PSTN and public land mobile network (PLMN).
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Most VoIP implementations support E.164 to allow calls to be routed to and from VoIP subscribers and the PSTN/PLMN.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP implementations can also allow other identification techniques to be used.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, Skype allows subscribers to choose *Skype names* (usernames) whereas SIP implementations can use Uniform Resource Identifier (URIs) similar to email addresses.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Often VoIP implementations employ methods of translating non-E.164 identifiers to E.164 numbers and vice versa, such as the Skype-In service provided by Skype and the E.164 number to URI mapping (ENUM) service in IMS and SIP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Echo can also be an issue for PSTN integration.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Common causes of echo include impedance mismatches in analog circuitry and an acoustic path from the receive to transmit signal at the receiving end.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Local number portability (LNP) and mobile number portability (MNP) also impact VoIP business.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Number portability is a service that allows a subscriber to select a new telephone carrier without requiring a new number to be issued.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Typically, it is the responsibility of the former carrier to "map" the old number to the undisclosed number assigned by the new carrier.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This is achieved by maintaining a database of numbers.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A dialed number is initially received by the original carrier and quickly rerouted to the new carrier.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Multiple porting references must be maintained even if the subscriber returns to the original carrier.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) mandates carrier compliance with these consumer-protection stipulations.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In November 2007, the FCC in the United States released an order extending number portability obligations to interconnected VoIP providers and carriers that support VoIP providers.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A voice call originating in the VoIP environment also faces least-cost routing (LCR) challenges to reach its destination if the number is routed to a mobile phone number on a traditional mobile carrier.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] LCR is based on checking the destination of each telephone call as it is made, and then sending the call via the network that will cost the customer the least.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This rating is subject to some debate, given the complexity of call routing created by number portability.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] With MNP in place, LCR providers can no longer rely on using the network root prefix to determine how to route a call.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Instead, they must now determine the actual network of every number before routing the call.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Therefore, VoIP solutions also need to handle MNP when routing a voice call.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In countries without a central database, like the UK, it may be necessary to query the mobile network about which home network a mobile phone number belongs to.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] As the popularity of VoIP increases in the enterprise markets because of LCR options, VoIP needs to provide a certain level of reliability when handling calls.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A telephone connected to a land line has a direct relationship between a telephone number and a physical location, which is maintained by the telephone company and available to emergency responders via the national emergency response service centers in the form of emergency subscriber lists.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] When an emergency call is received by a center, the location is automatically determined from its databases and displayed on the operator console.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In IP telephony, no such direct link between location and communications end point exists.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Even a provider having wired infrastructure, such as a DSL provider, may know only the approximate location of the device, based on the IP address allocated to the network router and the known service address.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Some ISPs do not track the automatic assignment of IP addresses to customer equipment.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] IP communication provides for device mobility.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, a residential broadband connection may be used as a link to a virtual private network of a corporate entity, in which case the IP address being used for customer communications may belong to the enterprise, not the residential ISP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Such off-premises extensions may appear as part of an upstream IP PBX.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] On mobile devices, e.g., a 3G handset or USB wireless broadband adapter, the IP address has no relationship with any physical location known to the telephony service provider, since a mobile user could be anywhere in a region with network coverage, even roaming via another cellular company.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] At the VoIP level, a phone or gateway may identify itself by its account credentials with a Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) registrar.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In such cases, the Internet telephony service provider (ITSP) knows only that a particular user's equipment is active.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Service providers often provide emergency response services by agreement with the user who registers a physical location and agrees that, if an emergency number is called from the IP device, emergency services are provided to that address only.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Such emergency services are provided by VoIP vendors in the United States by a system called Enhanced 911 (E911), based on the Wireless Communications and Public Safety Act.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The VoIP E911 emergency-calling system associates a physical address with the calling party's telephone number.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] All VoIP providers that provide access to the public switched telephone network are required to implement E911, a service for which the subscriber may be charged.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] "VoIP providers may not allow customers to opt out of 911 service." The VoIP E911 system is based on a static table lookup.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Unlike in cellular phones, where the location of an E911 call can be traced using assisted GPS or other methods, the VoIP E911 information is accurate only if subscribers keep their emergency address information current.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Sending faxes over VoIP networks is sometimes referred to as Fax over IP (FoIP).
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Transmission of fax documents was problematic in early VoIP implementations, as most voice digitization and compression codecs are optimized for the representation of the human voice and the proper timing of the modem signals cannot be guaranteed in a packet-based, connectionless network.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A standards-based solution for reliably delivering fax-over-IP is the T.38 protocol.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The T.38 protocol is designed to compensate for the differences between traditional packet-less communications over analog lines and packet-based transmissions, which are the basis for IP communications.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The fax machine may be a standard device connected to an analog telephone adapter (ATA), or it may be a software application or dedicated network device operating via an Ethernet interface.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Originally, T.38 was designed to use UDP or TCP transmission methods across an IP network.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Some newer high-end fax machines have built-in T.38 capabilities, which are connected directly to a network switch or router.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In T.38 each packet contains a portion of the data stream sent in the previous packet.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Two successive packets have to be lost to actually lose data integrity.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Telephones for traditional residential analog service are usually connected directly to telephone company phone lines, which provide direct current to power most basic analog handsets independently of locally available electrical power.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP phones and VoIP telephone adapters connect to routers or cable modems, which typically depend on the availability of mains electricity or locally generated power.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP service providers use customer premises equipment (e.g., cable modems) with battery-backed power supplies to assure uninterrupted service for up to several hours in case of local power failures.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Such battery-backed devices are typically designed for use with analog handsets.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP service providers implement services to route calls to other telephone services of the subscriber, such as a cellular phone, in the event that the customer's network device is inaccessible to terminate the call.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure calls are possible using standardized protocols such as Secure Real-time Transport Protocol.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Most of the facilities for creating a secure telephone connection over traditional phone lines, such as digitizing and digital transmission, are already in place with VoIP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] It is necessary only to encrypt and authenticate the existing data stream.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Automated software, such as a virtual PBX, may eliminate the need for personnel to greet and switch incoming calls.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The security concerns for VoIP telephone systems are similar to those of other Internet-connected devices.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This means that hackers with knowledge of VoIP vulnerabilities can perform denial-of-service attacks, harvest customer data, record conversations, and compromise voicemail messages.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Compromised VoIP user account or session credentials may enable an attacker to incur substantial charges from third-party services, such as long-distance or international calling.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The technical details of many VoIP protocols create challenges in routing VoIP traffic through firewalls and network address translators, used to interconnect to transit networks or the Internet.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Private session border controllers are often employed to enable VoIP calls to and from protected networks.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Other methods to traverse NAT devices involve assistive protocols such as STUN and Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE).
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Standards for securing VoIP are available in the Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP) and the ZRTP protocol for analog telephony adapters, as well as for some softphones.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] IPsec is available to secure point-to-point VoIP at the transport level by using opportunistic encryption.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Though many consumer VoIP solutions do not support encryption of the signaling path or the media, securing a VoIP phone is conceptually easier to implement using VoIP than on traditional telephone circuits.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A result of the lack of widespread support for encryption is that it is relatively easy to eavesdrop on VoIP calls when access to the data network is possible.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Free open-source solutions, such as Wireshark, facilitate capturing VoIP conversations.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Government and military organizations use various security measures to protect VoIP traffic, such as voice over secure IP (VoSIP), secure voice over IP (SVoIP), and secure voice over secure IP (SVoSIP).
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The distinction lies in whether encryption is applied in the telephone endpoint or in the network.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure voice over secure IP may be implemented by encrypting the media with protocols such as SRTP and ZRTP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure voice over IP uses Type 1 encryption on a classified network, such as SIPRNet.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Public Secure VoIP is also available with free GNU software and in many popular commercial VoIP programs via libraries, such as ZRTP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In June 2021, the National Security Agency (NSA) released comprehensive documents describing the four attack planes of a communications system – the network, perimeter, session controllers and endpoints – and explaining security risks and mitigation techniques for each of them.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice over IP protocols and equipment provide caller ID support that is compatible with the PSTN.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Many VoIP service providers also allow callers to configure custom caller ID information.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Wireline telephones which are manufactured in, imported to, or intended to be used in the US with Voice over IP service, on or after February 28, 2020, are required to meet the hearing aid compatibility requirements set forth by the Federal Communications Commission.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP has drastically reduced the cost of communication by sharing network infrastructure between data and voice.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A single broadband connection has the ability to transmit multiple telephone calls.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] As the popularity of VoIP grows, governments are becoming more interested in regulating VoIP in a manner similar to PSTN services.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Throughout the developing world, particularly in countries where regulation is weak or captured by the dominant operator, restrictions on the use of VoIP are often imposed, including in Panama where VoIP is taxed, Guyana, where VoIP is prohibited.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In Ethiopia, where the government is nationalizing telecommunication service, it is a criminal offense to offer services using VoIP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The country has installed firewalls to prevent international calls from being made using VoIP.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] These measures were taken after the popularity of VoIP reduced the income generated by the state-owned telecommunications company.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In Canada, the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission regulates telephone service, including VoIP telephony service.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP services operating in Canada are required to provide 9-1-1 emergency service.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] A general distinction is usually made between VoIP services that function over managed networks (via broadband connections) and VoIP services that function over unmanaged networks (essentially, the Internet).
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The relevant EU Directive is not clearly drafted concerning obligations that can exist independently of market power (e.g., the obligation to offer access to emergency calls), and it is impossible to say definitively whether VoIP service providers of either type are bound by them.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In Oman, it is illegal to provide or use unauthorized VoIP services, to the extent that websites of unlicensed VoIP providers have been blocked.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Violations may be punished with fines of 50,000 Omani Rial (about 130,317 US dollars), a two-year prison sentence or both.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In 2009, police raided 121 Internet cafes throughout the country and arrested 212 people for using or providing VoIP services.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In September 2017, Saudi Arabia lifted the ban on VoIPs, in an attempt to reduce operational costs and spur digital entrepreneurship.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In the United Arab Emirates (UAE), it is illegal to provide or use unauthorized VoIP services.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Websites of unlicensed VoIP providers have been blocked.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP services, such as Skype, were allowed.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In January 2018, internet service providers in UAE blocked all VoIP apps, including Skype, but permitting only 2 government-approved VoIP apps (C'ME and BOTIM).
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In opposition, a petition on *Change.org* garnered over 5000 signatures, in response to which the website was blocked in UAE.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] On March 24, 2020, the United Arab Emirates loosened restrictions on VoIP services earlier prohibited in the country, to ease communication during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] However, popular instant messaging applications such as WhatsApp, Skype, and FaceTime remained blocked from being used for voice and video calls, constricting residents to use paid services from the country's state-owned telecom providers.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In India, it is legal to use VoIP, but it is illegal to have VoIP gateways inside India.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] This effectively means that people who have PCs can use them to make a VoIP call to other computers but not to a normal phone number.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Foreign-based VoIP server services are illegal to use in India.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Internet telephony is permitted to the ISP with restrictions.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] PC / a device / Adapter conforming to the standard of any international agencies like ITU or IETF, etc., in India to PSTN/PLMN abroad.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Any device / Adapter conforming to standards of International agencies like ITU, IETF etc., connected to ISP node with static IP address to similar device / Adapter; within or outside India.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Except whatever is described in condition (ii) above, no other form of Internet Telephony is permitted.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In India no Separate Numbering Scheme is provided to the Internet Telephony.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Presently the 10-digit Numbering allocation based on E.164 is permitted to the Fixed Telephony, GSM, CDMA wireless service.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] For Internet Telephony, the numbering scheme shall only conform to IP addressing Scheme of Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA).
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Translation of E.164 number / private number to IP address allotted to any device and vice versa, by ISP to show compliance with IANA numbering scheme is not permitted.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The Internet Service Licensee is not permitted to have PSTN/PLMN connectivity.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice communication to and from a telephone connected to PSTN/PLMN and following E.164 numbering is prohibited in India.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In South Korea, only providers registered with the government are authorized to offer VoIP services.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Unlike many VoIP providers, most of whom offer flat rates, Korean VoIP services are generally metered and charged at rates similar to terrestrial calling.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Foreign VoIP providers encounter high barriers to government registration.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] In the United States, the FCC requires all interconnected VoIP service providers to comply with requirements comparable to those for traditional telecommunications service providers.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP operators also receive the benefit of certain US telecommunications regulations, including an entitlement to interconnection and exchange of traffic with incumbent local exchange carriers via wholesale carriers.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Providers of *nomadic* VoIP service—those who are unable to determine the location of their users—are exempt from state telecommunications regulation.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] Another legal issue that the US Congress is debating concerns changes to the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The issue in question is calls between Americans and foreigners.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] The NSA is not authorized to tap Americans' conversations without a warrant—but the Internet, and specifically VoIP does not draw as clear a line to the location of a caller or a call's recipient as the traditional phone system does.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] As VoIP's low cost and flexibility convince more and more organizations to adopt the technology, surveillance for law enforcement agencies becomes more difficult.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has also increased federal security concerns because VoIP and similar technologies have made it more difficult for the government to determine where a target is physically located when communications are being intercepted, and that creates a whole set of new legal challenges.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] Danny Cohen first demonstrated a form of packet voice in 1973 which was developed into Network Voice Protocol which operated across the early ARPANET.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] On the early ARPANET, real-time voice communication was not possible with uncompressed pulse-code modulation (PCM) digital speech packets, which had a bit rate of 64 kbps, much greater than the 2.4 kbps bandwidth of early modems.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] The solution to this problem was linear predictive coding (LPC), a speech coding data compression algorithm that was first proposed by Fumitada Itakura of Nagoya University and Shuzo Saito of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in 1966.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC was capable of speech compression down to 2.4 kbps, leading to the first successful real-time conversation over ARPANET in 1974, between Culler-Harrison Incorporated in Goleta, California, and MIT Lincoln Laboratory in Lexington, Massachusetts.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC has since been the most widely used speech coding method.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] Code-excited linear prediction (CELP), a type of LPC algorithm, was developed by Manfred R.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC algorithms remain an audio coding standard in modern VoIP technology.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] In the two decades following the 1974 demo, various forms of packet telephony were developed and industry interest groups formed to support the new technologies.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] Soon after it became an established area of interest in commercial labs of the major IT concerns, notably at AT&T, where Marian Croak and her team filed many patents related to the technology.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] By the late 1990s, the first softswitches became available, and new protocols, such as H.323, MGCP and Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) gained widespread attention.
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] In the early 2000s, the proliferation of high-bandwidth always-on Internet connections to residential dwellings and businesses spawned an industry of Internet telephony service providers (ITSPs).
[src:sip-protocol/voice-over-ip-p02] The development of open-source telephony software, such as Asterisk PBX, fueled widespread interest and entrepreneurship in voice-over-IP services, applying new Internet technology paradigms, such as cloud services to telephony.
